A frame is a snapshot of game state with features at some time t.
Let NUM_FRAMES = 4.
I wanna have NUM_FRAMES: t, t+1, t+10, t_resolved,
where t_resolved is the time in the future when all moving ships have resolved (landed).

Let ACTIONS_DIM = 2 for encoder geometry tensors:
    action bin 0 is noop metadata.
    action bin 1 is 100%, sending every ship currently on the source planet to
    the selected target.

The policy action space is separate from the encoder geometry tensor. The
reference-PPO pipeline uses one categorical:
    action 0: global noop.
    action 1 + source_slot * 44 + target_slot: send 100% of ships from source
        to target.

Launch actions are invalid if there are insufficient ships at the source planet.
Launch actions are invalid if the source planet is not under ally control.
The global noop action remains valid.

An action (i, j, count) is invalid if the trajectory caused from sending `count` ships from i to j, 
is not "clean" - i.e. the ships don't arrive at the destination in the future - this could be
because they intersect with another planet or intersect the sun.
(I don't see any other reason for obstruction.)

The copied reference PPO output action space is therefore one categorical with
1 + 44 * 44 = 1937 logits. `features.discrete_action_mask` builds this from the
Rust feature `mask[:, :, SEND_ALL_ACTION]` and prepends the global noop.

A planet token (TOKEN_DIM = 11, see features.rs::fill_token):
    * is_mine          (0/1)
    * is_enemy         (0/1)
    * is_neutral       (0/1)
    * is_comet         (0/1)
    * is_orbiting      (0/1)
    * production       (log-normalized)
    * ships            (log-normalized)
    * x                (/100)
    * y                (/100)
    * dist_to_sun      (/100)
    * angular_velocity (board orbital rate /0.05 for orbiting planets, else 0;
                        comets get 0 — they ride comet paths, not orbits)

Global features (GLOBAL_DIM = 16, see features.rs::compute_globals). All floats,
no one-hot. "enemy" aggregates every non-self player (works for 2p and 4p).
score = planet_ships + fleet_ships. Shares are own/(own+enemy), 0.5 when both 0.
Diffs are own − enemy (signed-log); counts are /44; ship/production totals are
log-normalized.
    remaining          (turns left / episode_steps)
    own_score
    enemy_score
    neutral_ships
    own_planets
    enemy_planets
    neutral_planets
    own_production
    enemy_production
    own_fleet_ships
    enemy_fleet_ships
    score_share
    production_share
    planet_share
    score_diff         (named "diff", not "margin")
    production_diff
(kept own_score over own_ships since kaggle decides the winner by total ships =
"score"; own_ships would be just as clear.)

Each frame consists of 44 planet tokens.
Each frame also contains an asymmetric distances matrix D of dims (44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM)
where D[i][j][action_idx] is the number of turns required to send the ships from i to j, 
starting at this frame. Probably we keep this number as a float instead of one hot.

The current PyTorch PPO policy architecture is copied from rl_orbit_wars'
EntityTransformerPolicy. It encodes current-frame planet tokens and a global
token, runs a 3-layer / 4-head transformer over `[global, planets...]`, then
scores source-target pairs with:
    encoded_src, encoded_tgt, encoded_src - encoded_tgt, encoded_src * encoded_tgt,
    current-frame dx/dy/dist/inv_dist,
    globals.

The future-frame tensors remain in the feature dict for experimentation and
validation, but the closest rl_orbit_wars transformer port consumes first-frame
geometry in the action head. The original global noop head is preserved; the
ship-fraction head has length 1 because our only launch action is send-all.

For invalid actions probably just leave this at 0 and let valid action mask handle it.
So this is looking like (NUM_FRAMES, 44, 44, ACTIONS_DIM).

I also think normalising stuff would be good.
    * distances: 1/100
    * turns: 1/20
    * ships: log or something else
    * production: log or something else

Always validate / test to make ensure correctness.

encode_obs(obs, player) output dict (see features.rs::Features::into_py_dict).
Numeric tensors are flat 1-D numpy buffers (zero-copy, torch.from_numpy-ready);
reshape each with its paired `*_shape`. The rest are plain Python objects.

    planet_ids     list[int], len 44   slot -> planet id, -1 for empty slots
    num_planets    int                 count of real planets at frame t
    frame_offsets  list[int], len 4     turn offsets of the frames: [0, 1, 10, resolved]
    frame_planets  list[list[tuple]]   per-frame [(id, owner, x, y, ships), ...],
                                        present planets only. NOT a model input —
                                        raw state for validation/debugging.
    tokens         float32, flat        reshape (4, 44, 11)  = (NUM_FRAMES, slot, TOKEN_DIM)
    tokens_shape   tuple (4, 44, 11)
    globals        float32, flat        reshape (16,)       board-level summary at frame t
    globals_shape  tuple (16,)
    presence       float32, flat        reshape (4, 44)     1.0 where a slot holds a planet
    presence_shape tuple (4, 44)
    turns          float32, flat        reshape (4, 44, 44, 2) = (frame, src, tgt, action);
                                        turns-to-arrive /20, 0 if invalid
    turns_shape    tuple (4, 44, 44, 2)
    angles         float32, flat        reshape (44, 44, 2) launch angle (radians) to issue
                                        the move; 0 if invalid
    angles_shape   tuple (44, 44, 2)
    mask           uint8, flat          reshape (44, 44, 2) 1 = legal action now, else 0
    mask_shape     tuple (44, 44, 2)
    ship_counts    int64, flat          reshape (44, 44, 2) integer ships sent; 0 for noop/invalid
    ship_counts_shape tuple (44, 44, 2)
    reachable_mask uint8, flat          reshape (4, 44, 44, 2) 1 = clean launch reaches target
    reachable_mask_shape tuple (4, 44, 44, 2)

Python training converts `mask` into a flat discrete mask with shape (1937,):
    action_mask[0]    is global noop.
    action_mask[1:]   is the all-in source-target legality matrix flattened as
                      source-major `(44, 44)`.

The legacy SB3 helper path can still build `valid_actions_mask` with shape
(44, 46), but it is not used by `train/train.py`.
